Microbial natural products have always performed a prominent role in the history of drug discovery and development [1]. These second- ary metabolites have a remarkable range of biological activities which are mainly caused by their complicated scaffolds and different functional groups [2]. Various modiﬁcation reactions are involved in the biosynthesis of these bioactive natural products, which can be divided into three different stages: namely pre-assembly modiﬁca- tion, assembly line modiﬁcation, and post-assembly modiﬁcation. Undoubtedly, post-modiﬁcation is often the most important modiﬁ- cation that contributes to the structural diversity and good bio- including redox, logical activities of most natural products, methylation, glycosylation, acetylation, prenylation, halogenation, etc. [3]. In addition to traditional approaches for natural product discovery, combinatorial biosynthesis methods can also generate new derivatives with improved properties [3]. In recent years, remarkable efforts have been carried out on both normal and unusual sugars, since they have a profound impact on the properties of the bioactive natural products [4]. Therefore, it is meaningful to develop some combinatorial biosynthetic approaches which can sugar moieties and generate novel glycosylated modify the derivatives.

Trioxacarcins (TXNs), belonging to the anthracycline family nat- ural products, were ﬁrst isolated from Streptomyces bottropensis NRRL 12051 by Tomita et al. in 1981 [5]. These compounds were also produced by the marine derived S. sp. B8652 according to Maskey’s research in 2004 [6]. All the TXNs exhibit high anti- bacterial activity towards Gram-positive bacteria, and some also show extraordinary anti-malaria and anti-tumor activities [5]. Trioxacarcin A (TXN-A) is clearly the most active molecule with a mean IC70-value of 0.001 μg/ml lines [6]. Anthracyclines contain a planar aromatic ring system with one or more sugar residues attached to it. Notable structural features of © The Author(s) 2019. For permissions, please e-mail: journals.permissions@oup.com TXNs include the spiro epoxy unit at the highly oxidized polycyclic skeleton, three ketal (hemiketal) groups at four contiguous carbon atoms and two special deoxyglycosyl moieties (Fig. 1A). TXNs util- ize their epoxide groups to intercalate and alkylate DNA by binding covalently to guanine N7, while interacting with both grooves of the DNA by positioning the C4-sugar in the minor groove and the C13- sugar in the major groove [7]. Kosinostatin (KST) [8], also belong- ing to anthracycline antibiotics and possessing highly anti-tumor activity, shares a same glycosyl moiety with TXN-A. Our laboratory is committed to the biosynthetic studies of TXNs and KST for many years. We cloned their biosynthetic gene clusters and proposed the biosynthetic pathway [9]. Herein, we attempt to change the hydro- philicity and overall topology of TXN-A and KST by modifying the structure of the glycosyl moiety.

Staphylococcus aureus var. suzhoueusis var. Yen SP-371 was ﬁrst isolated from the soil of Dongshan, Suzhou, Jiangsu Province in June 1981. We sequenced the genome of this strain and found a gene cluster tjh which encodes a novel type II polyketide compound. Based on the bioinformatic analysis, we speculate that tjhB6 may encode a pyridoxamine 5′-monophosphate-dependent NDP-hexose 3-dehydratase which should be closely related to the biosynthesis of the attached sugars. In this study, we engineered S. bottropensis NRRL 12051 and Micromonospora sp. TP-A0468 (a KST produ- cer) genome by integrating tjhB6 to them respectively. Isolation and structural characterization of newly accumulated compound demon- strated that this combinatorial biosynthetic approach could success- fully modify the sugar moiety of TXN-A. What’s more, the evidence of the increase in production of deoxy-isoquinocycline B [10] further supported our assertion concerning the role of this enzyme. Our group has been working on biosynthesis of natural products containing sugar modiﬁcations for many years. By analyzing the biosynthetic gene clusters of TXN-A and KST, we found that txnB3 and txnB4 share high homology with kstD7 and kstD8, respectively. In our previous work, we sur- mised that they encode a two-component pyruvate dehydrogenase- like enzyme that is responsible for the attachment of the two-carbon side chain derived from pyruvate [9]. In a recent study, we found two homologous genes of txnB3/txnB4 in S. aureus var. suzhoueusis var. Yen SP-371, tjhB9/tjhB10. Around tjhB9/tjhB10, a gene tjhB6 encoding a pyridoxamine 5′-monophosphate-dependent NDP-hexose 3-dehydratase is present. We speculated that if tjhB6 is integrated into S. bottropensis NRRL 12051, a new derivative of TXN-A lacking the hydroxyl group at C-3″ can be obtained (Fig. 1A).

In order to verify our conjecture, we ﬁrst added the strong pro- moters ermEp* or kasOp in front of tjhB6 and constructed them into pSET152 to obtain plasmids pSET-erm-B6 and pSET-kas-B6. Then we integrated these two plasmids into TXN-A-producing strain S. bottropensis NRRL 12051. Having mutants in our hand, we performed a small-scale fermentation. A new compound 2 elut- ing at 21 min was found in HPLC analysis, which exhibited a simi- lar UV–Vis absorption spectrum to that of TXN-A (Fig. 2A and Supplementary Fig. S1). Further analysis by LC-MS revealed that + compound 2 showed a molecular ion ([M + Na] ) at m/z = 883.44, which is consistent with our hypothesized product (Supplementary Fig. S2). In Fig. 2A, we can also conclude that the promoter kasOp is better than ermEp*. Therefore, we further carried out a large- scale fermentation (5 l) of the strain containing the plasmid pSET- kas-B6 and isolated a sufﬁcient amount of compound 2 for further Production of a trioxacarcin analog by combinatorial biosynthesis structural analysis. 1H NMR, 13C NMR and 2D NMR spectra demonstrated that the novel compound 2 was the target product we expected (Supplementary Table S1 and Supplementary Fig. S3).

To further test the capability of this method, we performed the same experiments in M. sp. TP-A0468. The small-scale fermentation broth was analyzed by HPLC (Fig. 2B) and we found that the main products were still KST (3) and isoquinocycline B (ISO, 4). In our past research, we isolated and identiﬁed deoxy-isoquinocycline B (5) [10]. Here, compared to the wild-type strain, we can see a signiﬁcant increase in the production of deoxy-isoquinocycline B. What’s more, a new peak was found around 14.5 min. Further analysis by LC-MS revealed that + this new compound 6 showed a molecular ion ([M + Na] ) at m/z = 601.41, which is consistent with that of deoxy-isoquinocycline B (Fig. 1B). Considering the evidence that KST and ISO always coexist in the fermentation broth, we speculate that compound 6 is very likely to be deoxygenated KST at C-3″, which was once ignored because of the trace amount. We then conducted in vitro cytotoxicity assays of TXN-B6 using cultured Jurkat cells. TXN-A shows signiﬁcant activity with an IC50 value of 0.894 ± 0.058 nM, while TXN-B6 shows a similar IC50 value of 1.05 ± 0.074 nM (Fig. 3 and Supplementary Table S2). As mentioned above, TXNs take advantage of the C13-sugar to interact with the major groove. The very similar activities of these two com- pounds indicate that the hydroxyl group at C-3″ of the C13-sugar has little effect on the inhibitory activity toward Jurkat cells. pathway of TXN-A and KST by combinatorial biosynthesis, and we have successfully modiﬁed the side chains of their glycosyl groups. We obtained TXN-B6 through large-scale fermentation and separation. TXN-A is a highly cytotoxic compound, and the activity of TXN-B6 is comparable. This study also conﬁrmed our hypothesis about the func- tion of tjhB6 and extended our understanding of glycosylation and combinatorial biosynthesis. We will continue to introduce more modiﬁ- cation genes, which will help us obtain more TXN analogs with higher anti-tumor activity or better physical and chemical properties, thereby providing candidate molecules for drug discovery.
